I am going to be sad to see this place close. Service was a 10, drinks were a 10 and so unique and lastly the food was a 12/10. Got the most popular item on the menu. The Brazilian fried chicken or frango a passarinho and it was phenomenal. It was unbreaded bone in fried chicken. It had a sweet yet smokey sauce on it and it was topped with cilantro and jalapeños which added to the whole flavor of the dish. As a side I got the Brazilian cheese bread which is in my opinion a better mozzarella stick because theres more cheese and it is less greasy. I would recommend to go here before it closes December 31st

This place has evolved and matured really nicely and I love coming here.  What was scorchingly hot and impossible to get into when it opened, has now become a lively, lovely neighborhood standby.  It is super comfortable and super tasty.  My wife, daughter, and I came for dinner on Sunday evening and the place was humming but not overrun.  Service was attentive and excellent and the pace of the meal was leisurely and relaxed, as it should be on a warm summer evening.  Just perfect.  Wine and cocktail service is outstanding, if not extensive.  My Caipirnha was terrific and not too sweet but with a good bite.  Too often this drink can be cloying if not handled well.  Dinner was excellent. Kale salad was creamy but with enough heat from the jalapeno to stand up to it.  Grilled Asparagus were tender and delicious. Empanadas were good but sort of boring. The whole fresh fish was absolutely delicious with an array of flavors that seemed more Asian than South American.  It was snapper on our evening but I'd order it regardless of the day's fish.  Pork Milenesa was good but a little dry and the hanger steak was expertly cooked and delicious.  This place has really matured and I love coming here for a more restrained, comfortable meal when I don't need to live on the edge with some hip newcomer.

This place was amazing. We came in without a reservation - while the place was mostly full, they were able to serve us dinner at the bar. The service was impeccable and timely. When the gelato for my apple pie empanada was forgotten (which was understandable given how busy the place was), they quickly brought it out, gave me an extra scoop and comped it. And oh man, the food, the food was great. You can tell a lot of thought went into the flavours and textures of the different dishes. The grilled pork chops may have been the best pork I've had - it was wonderfully moist and well flavoured. The cheese bread was another highlight. Overall, I highly recommend this place.

This place manages to combine a number of good qualities that you can't always find in one restaurant: food that is simultaneously homey and satiating but not boring; an atmosphere that's fairly chic but also cozy and welcoming. My friend and I came at 3:00 and ordered off the brunch menu: the feijoada burrito (black beans and rive with linguiça, scrambled eggs and  avocado in a grilled tortilla), the pão de queijo (small tapioca buns made with oil and cheese—surprisingly light and very delicious). We also ordered their tepache (pineapple juice infused with ginger and spices). Everything was great. I have very high standards for my food and am actually disappointed by most of the restaurants I've been to in Chicago (I'm from the central coast of California), but this place nailed it with respect to full-bodied flavors, a rich assortment of textures, and satisfying serving sizes. We stayed chatting for two an a half hours, by which time the sun had set and it looked like much of the staff was changing over. I was deeply impressed that the servers kept coming to refill our water glasses even half an hour after we had paid our checks. This place should be more crowded at 4:00 pm on a Saturday! (It started filling up very quickly after 5:00, so you might want to make a reservation.)

It's really sad when you're so excited about eating at a restaurant and before you can even take a bite of your food, the treatment by staff is so disgusting, you have to leave.  That's what happened to my group and I at La Sirena yesterday. My 3 friends and I decided to gather there for drinks and food. Understanding there were no reservations available, we opted for seating at the bar which was confirmed as first come, first served. Well, after almost 20 - 30 min of sitting at the bar chatting and preparing to order drinks and food, the hostess came by and asked us to give up our bar seats for a pair who arrived late for their reservation and thus had their table given to other guests. The hostess somehow decided that our group of 4 needed to give up 2 of our "first come, first served" seats for 2 guests who were late. Riddle me that?  Pretty upset my the experience, we decided to leave and try Wow Fun, where we walked in and received wonderful service and great food. It's worth noting that when we left La Sirena, I attempted to close out my single drink tab and the bartender whispered, "Don't worry, I'll cover the drink. I'm not sure what's happening but I'm sorry." At least there are SOME good staff left at La Sirena.

La Serena Clandestina had potential since there are no other Brazilian restaurants that I know in the area, but upon walking in, it might as well be modern American in the West Loop as it has the same warehouse feel as the rest of the area.  The food looks reasonably priced for a lunch, $12 for salad or bowl, but it is $2 more for avocado, $6 for a chicken breast or shrimp and double the price ($12) for beef.  I had a shrimp bowl that had slow cooked black beans, jasmine rice, chimichurri and 4 or 5 shrimp.  Everything tasted fine, but nothing special.  Beans, rice a little protein at that price seems like a bad deal.

Superb service at a sexy little Latin spot. ;)  My friend and I started our evening at the bar while we waited for our table to be ready. I ordered the "The Crying Game", a potent and manly cocktail from their Bebidas menu. It was served on the rocks and made with overproof rum, 2 other kinds of rum and bitters - with no true "mixer" it's strong. Perfection.  Once seated, we started with pan de queijo (cheese bread) - don't think of typical American cheesy bread from Dominos. It's more like a warm pillow of baked dough filled with a soft gooey cheese. Next, we ordered the garlic frites - crispy fries topped with a generous amount of herbs and salt and served with some bomb aoili! We also ordered the coxinha, a smoked chicken croquette - it was pretty good, but not a standout. We weren't too hungry so we didn't get entrees, but we did get DESSERT! The panna cotta was so damn good! Such a complex dish and variety of flavors packed into one amazing dish.  We loved the atmosphere here - the bartender that served us our drinks and our server were both amazing and attentive. The restaurant was dimly lit and quiet. It's a perfect date night spot - check it out.
Solid spot for dinner

Absolutely amazing food!  To start, the empanda was succulent and crunchy, if not a little on the "soupy" side in the interior (also very hot at first, let it cool before eating).  Moving on to the fish (bass?), it was prepped whole and cooked to perfection!  The garnish as well as the glaze/sauce was great, and the fish itself was perfectly tender and juicy.  Finally, the chocolate cake (tres leches) was soooooo good.  Will be returning next week!

Special spot, a notch above the other restaurants in the over saturated Chicago restaurant scene. Most importantly, the food was outstanding! The atmosphere was sophisticated and cool, vintage with a funky urban twist. I would have definitely given five stars, yet the pricing was slightly on the pretentious side. That being said....this location is the hottest restaurant scene in Chicago, so I expected the prices I paid. Ultimately, it was worth it. I had a great time. It was relaxed, it was cool and the food was top notch. I'll be back and if I have the same experience next time, they'll get that 5th star!

Not sure why this restaurant gets such good ratings.  We had 5 dishes and all were below par.  The rabbit cox coxinha was gummy and missing even a moderate hint of rabbit, the civiche was passable, as we're the head-on prawns (apart from the one that was raw) but the Farro winter  salad was too sweet for my taste.  However it should be said my wife did like it.  The wine list is limited.  All of the whites by the glass are  sweet in style!  All in all there's better choices all around.

Almost everything we had was incredible. Definitely worth getting the kale salad even if the idea that kale can taste good is met with skepticism. Best caipirinha I've had in Chicago so far. My one gripe is the donuts we had were overly spicy for a dessert and I didn't really care for the sweet potato flavored sauce, but I'm willing to chalk that up to personal preference.  La Sirena is a very small establishment so reservations are usually required and the acoustics are a little ear-grating, but the food is not to be missed.

All dishes were top notch. Rice dish, prawns, grilled fish, beet salad with mascarpone cheese...incredible. Fantastic cocktails and dessert too. Love the bar upfront for a drink too.  Pro tip: Get there early and chat with the bartender about some of the Latin American ingredients that are featured as he prepares a cocktail that's sure to please.
Great food and service.  Cocktails are good too.  You'll enjoy the Brazillian fare here.  I would go back.

One of my favorite lunch spots in the West Loop – I always love the kale salad and grilled chicken hearts. Very laidback but with unique flavors you won't find elsewhere and chef makes his own hot sauces!
The best part were the apps.  The main dishes seemed to lack flavor or character.  It was a toss up in my view, an average attempt at fusion.
brilliant

Great service, chill ambiance, food was awesome, the waiter was able to recommend wines to go with our meal. We had ceviche, rabbit arepas, and the sweetbread dish. I would recommend any of them! Enjoy!!!

I think this place is OK. The hostess seems very pretentious and the food served isn't special. I think it is overvalued and unoriginal. They serve pork cutlet...which is essentially Japanese Tonkatsu! And they charge $25 for it. For good measure, I went back here again for the drinks and for the awesome Tres Leches I had the first time. However, they didn't have it and I was disappointed (menu for dessert changes).

Solid restaurant. We had their La Colombe coffee collaboration brunch and between the three of us, we tasted the majority of the offerings. Everything was great. Service was fantastic and the restaurant was small and cute. Prices were equivalent to most of the other restaurants on Restaurant Row. Looking forward to returning to try out their normal menu!
Nice ambiance. Had to dine at the bar since no tables available. Empanadas were great and the drinks. Main meal was sirloin and was undercooked. Would try again. Pricey for what you get tho.

The atmosphere of this latin infused restaurant is great. This is the perfect spot to meet up with a girlfriend and share a drink and a meal, or go on a romantic date. The portions are perfect for sharing, I'd highly recommend the empanadas and the tres leches dessert.
I would keep going back just for the brussel sprout salad alone, but the excellent menu, cocktails, ambiance, and scale of this place make it a pleasant setting for good company and conversation.

I would give 0 stars if I could!!! This is the worst experience I ever had! Food was horrible! Disgusting! They can't say they are a Brazilian restaurant! I had the moqueca, it was overly salty and almost no fish in it, the chicken hearts was overly done, we sent it back, but the new ones had no salt at all! It comes wit a hot sauce that doesn't make sense ( in Brasil we don't put hot sauce in chicken hearts), and even my husband who loves spicy foods said it didn't go well! The kale salad w jalapeño don't make sense either! And all that bad food was very expensive! Too bad, because the decor is beautiful and the music is nice ( the only real Brazilian thing there!).

A friend took me here a few weeks back. We had a fantastic dinner! Great atmosphere & amazing food! Loved the Empanadas & the Brussels Sprout Salad. Everything was delicious. Good beer selection as well. Friendly wait staff as well! I've been in a few times since for lunch. Cool to sit up at the bar & have a kick ass lunch break!

Complex flavors, layers of flavor -- every foodie buzzword could be used to describe the dishes here. I had the short ribs, cilantro risotto and meat empanada, all exotic yet homey. The cocktails are also a highlight with a focus on Brazilian originals like the caipirinha. They take reservation so get yours today.
Have eaten there once and the food was very good. Small place that can be hard to get into, but definitely worth checking out. Just off of Randolph on Fulton Market.
Stopped in here simply for a cocktail while waiting for our reservation at Next. Got some specialty drinks, which were really good. Hoping to go back here sometime soon for dinner.

Came here for the first time on a Friday night around 9pm and had a great time. There wasn't a wait, but the place had a decent amount of action.  The octopus salad had great acidity, and the octopus was perfectly tender. The sweetbreads were massive and creamy, and the giardiniera added a nice sweet heat. The thin cut short rib was a refreshing change from any I've had before. The brussel sprouts were a pleasant surprise and had almonds for days.  Had a couple cocktails, though I can't remember their names, were both good accompaniments to a well rounded experience. Will definitely be back soon.
Love this place!   Off the beaten path of Randolph, great vibe, fabulous food and excellent drinks from the bar.  You simply can't go wrong here.

The seafood stew is amazing.  They serve it over a special rice/sauce mixture that is super tasty and combine shrimp, prawns, mussles into it.  Great to share with 2 people.  Most items are meant for sharing (tapas style).  Anything seafood here is amazing.  Unique drinks and wine.  They also have yummy empanadas!  They now accept reservations, but I prefer sitting at the bar.

great food spent fathersday there with my family wehad lamb s hank  eggs benedict fries five rabbit beer  shrimo The owner came over we had a nice conversation...the service was good except the server did not ask if we wanted coffee or desert
Fun menu, good price point and excellent service. I will return

I will keep this simple and to the point. Food is not as good as the hype that the management might be trying to create. This is Chicago, a foodie paradise, so this place just doesn't cut it. There wasn't a single dish that made me say I need to try this again. We had six in our group and we shared, so I was able to try several items on the menu. Service was slow and staff just lacked interest. Also everyone in our table said we smelled urine as we walked into the restaurant. It maybe due to the close proximity of the bathroom to the restaurant. My point is that there are several other restaurants in Chicago that is truly worth your money.

I love going here after work for one of the amazingly awesome drinks.  The staff has no airs about them and I keep coming back to try alk of the different empanadas, ceviche and daily specials.  The moqueca is a crowd pleaser. I think I have tried all of drink specials on the menu but my two favorites are the pisco sour and papi chuli.

Sweet tiny infant baby Jesus. This is one of the premier restaurants in Chicago. Literally some of the best food I have ever eaten in my entire life. If you are not giving this place a try you are stupid and you should stop reading my reviews. Seriously, stop reading.
Amazing drinks and food here for dinner. Caipirinhas were delicious and the Swordfish Ceviche was outstanding.
